Diagnostic warnings when an out-of-dialect operator is used.

The dialect-selection contract documented in
clautolisp-user-manual.org § Dialect selection and in
clautolisp-specifications.org § Dialect selection states:

  "Whatever the dialect selected, all the operators are available.
   Only those that are not specifically inside the set defined by
   the dialect produce warnings when compiled and when used."

This issue tracks the warning machinery itself — currently the
runtime accepts every operator silently regardless of dialect.
The default-dialect.issue work added the contract to the spec
and the user-manual but deferred the warning implementation to
this dedicated track because it touches multiple layers and
needs design work.

Design questions to answer first:

  1. Source of truth — where is the per-dialect operator set
     defined? The autolisp-spec catalog (pages/symbols.txt) has
     a "kind" column per entry but no per-dialect availability
     bitmap. The closest existing data is in the Availability
     section of each Function Entry .org page. We may need to
     extend build-paged-spec.el to emit a per-symbol availability
     bitmap (autocad / bricscad / clautolisp tri-state) into a
     new artefact (e.g. pages/availability.txt).

  2. Warn on read or on first use? Read-time warning catches
     dead code, but conflicts with macros and conditional
     compilation. First-use warning catches only live calls but
     adds runtime cost. Probably first-use (or first-resolve),
     emitted once per (operator, session) pair.

  3. Warning channel — *error-output*? a separate stream
     accessible from AutoLISP? bound to a session-level toggle
     so production code can silence it?

  4. Strict / lax — under :strict dialect, do all dialect-
     specific operators warn (autocad-only AND bricscad-only)?
     Probably yes. Under :clautolisp, dialect-specific operators
     from any vendor warn unless reimplemented in clautolisp.

Acceptance:

  - A per-symbol availability data file derived from the spec
    (autolisp-spec build outputs it; clautolisp install consumes
    it).
  - A new mechanism in the runtime that, on the FIRST call to an
    operator outside the current dialect's set, emits a single
    diagnostic per (operator, session) pair to *error-output*.
  - The diagnostic is silenced by *AUTOLISP-WARN-OUT-OF-DIALECT*
    bound to NIL.
  - Tests: under --strict, calling a bricscad-only operator emits
    exactly one warning; the second call is silent.
  - User-manual + specifications updated to point at the
    implementation (currently they point at this issue).

Out of scope:

  - Compile-time warnings (issue title says "compiled and when
    used" but clautolisp has no separate compile step today; the
    "when used" half is the practical contract).
  - Cross-dialect operator polyfills (separate work; see
    missing-functions.issue for the inventory).
